The best approach for `File.ReadAllText`, `File.WriteAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides the interface + mock infrastructure.

## Setup

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

## Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

## Inject into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

## Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") },
    { "/data/", new MockDirectoryData() }
});

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.True(service.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Read("/data/config.json"));

service.Write("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
```

## Migration summary

1. Replace `using System.IO;` static calls with calls on the injected `IFileSystem`
2. `File.ReadAllText(...)` → `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)`
3. `File.WriteAllText(...)` → `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)`
4. `Directory.Exists(...)` → `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)`

The API surface mirrors `System.IO` exactly, so the refactor is mechanical — just swap the receiver. No need to write a custom wrapper for these.
